@JCab09 Would you mind showing the content of custom_lib.hpp? Does it include "core/common/status.h" ?

@snnn Yes it does. I was following this guideline: https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/reference/operators/add-custom-op.html
which links to this file: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/onnxruntime/test/testdata/custom_op_library/custom_op_library.cc
There the "core/common/status.h" header file is also included.  That header is apparently needed for the ORT_TRY - ORT_CATCH statements at the bottom of said file.

It does compile though, when I do not include "core/common/status.h" and replace ORT_TRY-ORT_CATCH with the regular try-catch statements.

EDIT: I also compiled the newest GSL Library on windows, but it doesn't provide the required header file.

I cannot make comments on the code. I am not familiar with it. But, I can say: 
If you need to use "core/common/common.h" or  "core/common/status.h", you need to statically link to onnxruntime_common static library which we do not distribute and needs be built from source. Generally speaking, I do not recommend doing so.  They are internal APIs. 
Public APIs use OrtStatus, or Ort::Status.  Like this: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime-inference-examples/blob/main/c_cxx/fns_candy_style_transfer/fns_candy_style_transfer.c#L23 . They do not use onnxruntime::Status. 
We do not use GNU GSL. We use [Microsoft GSL library](https://github.com/microsoft/GSL) internally. Microsoft GSL library is a header-only library. It does not need be compiled.  And it should not matter if you do not use onnxruntime internal APIs.
